## 5. `mc_att_control` internals — *what consumes `vehicle_attitude_setpoint` and produces `vehicle_rates_setpoint`*

`Run()` body: `mc_att_control_main.cpp:192-336`. Triggered by `vehicle_attitude` callbacks (i.e. on every EKF2 attitude update).

### 5.1 Inputs

| Subscription | Use |
|---|---|
| `vehicle_attitude` | feedback $q$ — the EKF2 estimate (drives `Run()`) |
| `vehicle_attitude_setpoint` (`:227`) | the setpoint $q_d$ — copied into `_attitude_control` at `:233` |
| `vehicle_angular_velocity` | feedback $\boldsymbol\omega$ — used for the rate D-term |
| `manual_control_setpoint` | sticks (only in stabilized mode where `generate_attitude_setpoint()` runs) |
| `vehicle_control_mode` | gates attitude vs manual-gen branches |
| `autotune_attitude_control_status` | optional autotune injection (`:308-316`) |

### 5.2 `AttitudeControl::update()` math  (`AttitudeControl.cpp:55-112`)

PX4's MC attitude controller implements the **reduced-+-full-attitude blend with yaw weight** from Brescianini, Hehn & D'Andrea, *Nonlinear Quadrocopter Attitude Control* (ETH Zurich, 2013).

**Reduced attitude** prioritises roll / pitch — the rotation that aligns the current and desired thrust directions only:
$$
\mathbf{e}_z = R(q)\,\hat{z}, \qquad
\mathbf{e}_{z,d} = R(q_d)\,\hat{z}, \qquad
q_{d,\text{red}} = \mathrm{Quat}(\mathbf{e}_z \to \mathbf{e}_{z,d})
$$

**Full attitude** then refines the yaw by a weighted partial rotation:
$$
q_{\text{mix}} = q_{d,\text{red}}^{-1} \otimes q_d \;\;(\text{canonical}),\qquad
\tilde{q}_d = q_{d,\text{red}} \otimes
\begin{pmatrix}
\cos\!\big(w \cdot \arccos q_{\text{mix},0}\big) \\
0 \\
0 \\
\sin\!\big(w \cdot \arcsin q_{\text{mix},3}\big)
\end{pmatrix}
$$
with $w =$ `MC_YAW_WEIGHT`. The proportional gain is rescaled by $1/w$ in `setProportionalGain()` (`:50-52`) so the closed-loop response on yaw is preserved.

**Quaternion attitude error** (rotation from current to desired):
$$
q_e = q^{-1} \otimes \tilde{q}_d
$$

**Half-angle axis-angle representation** (taking care of the antipodal ambiguity via `canonical()`):
$$
\mathbf{e}_q = 2 \cdot \mathrm{imag}\!\big(\mathrm{canonical}(q_e)\big)
$$

**Rate setpoint** = P − D + yaw feed-forward (the yaw-FF is expressed in world Z then rotated into body via $q^{-1}\hat{z}$):
$$
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{sp} \;=\; \mathbf{K}_p^{att} \odot \mathbf{e}_q \;-\; \mathbf{K}_d^{att} \odot \boldsymbol{\omega} \;+\; R(q)^{T}\hat{z} \cdot \dot{\psi}_{sp,FF}
$$

with $\mathbf{K}_p^{att}$ = `MC_{ROLL,PITCH,YAW}_P`, $\mathbf{K}_d^{att}$ = `MC_{ROLL,PITCH,YAW}_D` (the D-term is a KW fork extension; upstream PX4 sets these to zero).

Finally each axis is hard-clipped to `MC_{ROLLRATE,PITCHRATE,YAWRATE}_MAX`.

### 5.3 Output

```cpp
// mc_att_control_main.cpp:319-326
vehicle_rates_setpoint_s rates_setpoint{};
rates_setpoint.roll  = rates_sp(0);
rates_setpoint.pitch = rates_sp(1);
rates_setpoint.yaw   = rates_sp(2);
_thrust_setpoint_body.copyTo(rates_setpoint.thrust_body);    // passthrough from attitude_sp
rates_setpoint.timestamp = hrt_absolute_time();
_vehicle_rates_setpoint_pub.publish(rates_setpoint);
```

`thrust_body` is passed through unchanged from the attitude setpoint — the attitude controller has no influence on collective thrust.

