## 6. `mc_rate_control` internals — *what consumes `vehicle_rates_setpoint` and produces `vehicle_torque_setpoint` + `vehicle_thrust_setpoint`*

`Run()` body: `MulticopterRateControl.cpp:128-297`. Triggered by `vehicle_angular_velocity` callbacks (the gyro post-filter chain published by `sensors/vehicle_angular_velocity/` — see `imu_clarification_2026-05-14.*` for that side).

### 6.1 Inputs

| Subscription | Use | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `vehicle_angular_velocity` | feedback $\boldsymbol{\omega}$ (`xyz[3]`) and $\dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}}$ (`xyz_derivative[3]`) | triggers `Run()`; the rate D-term uses the *derivative* field, which is computed pre-LPF — see [[imu_clarification_2026-05-14]] §3.2 |
| `vehicle_rates_setpoint` | desired body rates $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{sp}$ from `mc_att_control` | `:208-215` |
| `manual_control_setpoint` | sticks (acro + pure-manual paths) | |
| `vehicle_control_mode` | branch selection | |
| `control_allocator_status` | anti-windup feedback from the allocator | `:228-245` |
| `vehicle_land_detected` | gates integral inhibit | |
| `battery_status` | optional torque/thrust scaling | only if `MC_BAT_SCALE_EN` |

### 6.2 Mode branching  (lines 178-215)

```cpp
if (manual && !attitude && !rates) {        // pure-manual passthrough
    handle_manual_mode(dt);                  // publishes τ + F directly at :121-122
}
else if (manual && !attitude) {             // ACRO
    // synthesise _rates_setpoint from sticks (lines 189-205)
    // publish vehicle_rates_setpoint at :205 for logging
}
else if (_vehicle_rates_setpoint_sub.update(&v)) {   // normal: take from mc_att_control
    _rates_setpoint(0..2) = v.roll/pitch/yaw;        // NaN-guarded
    _thrust_setpoint     = v.thrust_body;
}

if (flag_control_rates_enabled) {            // run PID and publish τ + F at :285,289
    ...
}
```

### 6.3 `RateControl::update()` math  (`lib/rate_control/rate_control.cpp:71-86`)

**PID with feed-forward** — the D-term uses the **measured angular acceleration** (`xyz_derivative` from the gyro module), not derivative-of-error:

$$
\mathbf{e}_\omega = \boldsymbol{\omega}_{sp} - \boldsymbol{\omega}, \qquad
\boldsymbol{\tau} \;=\; \mathbf{K}_p^{rate} \odot \mathbf{e}_\omega \;+\; \boldsymbol{\omega}_{int} \;-\; \mathbf{K}_d^{rate} \odot \dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}} \;+\; \mathbf{K}_{ff}^{rate} \odot \boldsymbol{\omega}_{sp}
$$

with $\mathbf{K}_p^{rate}$ = `MC_{ROLLRATE,PITCHRATE,YAWRATE}_P` etc.

**Non-linear integral gain reduction** (`updateIntegral()`, `:101-108`) — counteracts integral bounce-back after large setpoint changes (e.g. flips):

$$
i_{\text{factor}}(i) \;=\; \max\!\bigg(0, \; 1 - \Big(\dfrac{e_{\omega,i}}{\,400°/\text{s}\,}\Big)^{\!2}\bigg)
$$

so a 100°/s rate error keeps $i_{\text{factor}} \approx 0.94$, while a 200°/s rate error drops it to $0.75$. The integrator update is:

$$
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{int}(i) \;\mathrel{+}= \; i_{\text{factor}}(i) \cdot K_i(i) \cdot e_{\omega,i} \cdot dt, \qquad \text{constrained to } [-K_i^{lim}, K_i^{lim}]
$$

with $K_i^{lim}$ = `MC_{RR,PR,YR}_INT_LIM`.

**Anti-windup from allocator** (`:225-245`): if `control_allocator_status.torque_setpoint_achieved == false`, the per-axis `saturation_positive` / `saturation_negative` flags are set into `_rate_control` via `setSaturationStatus()`. (Note: in the current code, the integrator inhibit branches inside `updateIntegral()` are commented out — line 92-94, 96-98 — so the flags are recorded but not yet acted on. Effective anti-windup is still provided by the `K_i^{lim}` clamp.)

**Integral inhibit on landed** (`:81-83`): `if (!landed) updateIntegral(...)` — when the vehicle is on the ground the integrator is frozen rather than reset, so a stand-up restart doesn't suddenly release stored error.

**Disarm reset** (`:220-223`): `_rate_control.resetIntegral()` is called when `!flag_armed || not rotary_wing`.

### 6.4 Battery scaling  (`:265-281`)

If `MC_BAT_SCALE_EN`, both torque and thrust are scaled by the current battery voltage ratio (`battery_status.scale`, the inverse-of-voltage-ratio computed in `battery_status` itself):

$$
\boldsymbol{\tau}_{out} = \mathrm{clip}\!\big(\boldsymbol{\tau} \cdot s_{batt}, \; -1, \; +1\big), \quad
\mathbf{F}_{out} = \mathrm{clip}\!\big(\mathbf{F} \cdot s_{batt}, \; -1, \; +1\big)
$$

so that a sagging battery doesn't lose effective gain at the actuator.

### 6.5 Output

```cpp
// MulticopterRateControl.cpp:283-289
vehicle_thrust_setpoint.timestamp_sample = angular_velocity.timestamp_sample;
vehicle_thrust_setpoint.timestamp        = hrt_absolute_time();
_vehicle_thrust_setpoint_pub.publish(vehicle_thrust_setpoint);

vehicle_torque_setpoint.timestamp_sample = angular_velocity.timestamp_sample;
vehicle_torque_setpoint.timestamp        = hrt_absolute_time();
_vehicle_torque_setpoint_pub.publish(vehicle_torque_setpoint);
```

Both messages share `timestamp_sample = angular_velocity.timestamp_sample` so the downstream allocator can correlate them.

The pure-manual passthrough (`handle_manual_mode()` at `:101-126`) is the **only path that injects a torque setpoint without running the PID loop**. It maps sticks directly:

```cpp
// :113-119
vehicle_torque_setpoint.xyz[0] =  manual_control_setpoint.roll;
vehicle_torque_setpoint.xyz[1] = -manual_control_setpoint.pitch;       // sign convention
vehicle_torque_setpoint.xyz[2] =  manual_control_setpoint.yaw;
vehicle_thrust_setpoint.xyz[2] = -0.5f * (manual_control_setpoint.throttle + 1.f);
```

The publication is still from `_vehicle_torque_setpoint_pub` — the topic-injection point is the same as the PID path (`vehicle_torque_setpoint`), so the allocator can't tell them apart.

